article.headline: Oregon 83, Arizona State 76
article.story: TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Luke Jackson knows when to take over a game. Against Arizona State, he spent much of the second half taking care of teammates like James Davis, Ian Crosswhite and Andre Joseph. Jackson had 21 points and a career-high 12 assists in Oregon's 83-76 win over the Sun Devils on Thursday night. "There's going to be times where coach wants me to try and create some shots for me, just because we get a little stagnant," Jackson said. "Other times, I get the ball to Mitch (Platt) and Ian and James and Dre, and tonight they were knocking down big shots. "I didn't even attack the basket the last eight minutes because those guys were really stepping up." Jackson, Davis and Joseph, the Ducks' third-year seniors, had never won in Tempe, where Oregon's last previous victory was on Feb. 5, 2000. All played a big role in this one. Davis scored 15 points and Joseph had all 14 of his in the second half, when no more than eight points separated the teams. "It was a key game for us," Davis said. "If we can establish the inside game like that (Platt and Crosswhite), that opens up the guards." Crosswhite scored 15 points and Platt, a freshman, had a season-high 13 and eight rebounds for Oregon (9-4, 4-2 Pac-10). Arizona State's Ike Diogu, scoreless for more than 13 minutes at the start, finished with 24 points to extend his national-best double-figure scoring streak to 47 games. He had nine rebounds. Stevie Moore scored 17 points and Jason Braxton had 13 and tied his career high with eight rebounds. But the Sun Devils (7-8, 1-5) couldn't profit from a 15-point win at Southern California on Saturday that snapped their five-game losing streak. "I'm miffed to try and find out why we don't come out with a greater sense of urgency in the first half," Arizona State coach Rob Evans said. "This has been a pattern with this ballclub all year long." Arizona State had a 20-8 run in only 4:05 of the second half to take a 60-56 lead on Moore's four-point play with 10:24 to go. But Jackson made a 3-pointer and, after a dunk by Braxton, Joseph made two free throws. The Ducks regained the lead, 63-62, on Crosswhite's tip-in with 6:45 to play. Joseph had two 3-pointers and Crosswhite scored five points in an 8-4 surge that left the Ducks ahead 75-70 with 3:11 remaining, and the Ducks won with accurate free-throw shooting. Jackson failed to score in the first six minutes, but banked in a jumper and made a 3-pointer 45 seconds apart during a 13-2 run that earned the Ducks a 15-7 lead with 12:23 left in the first half. Oregon's lead reached 25-12 on Jackson's three-point play off a putback with 7:50 to go. Diogu broke his scoring drought with a putback with 6:32 left and had 10 points by halftime, cutting the Sun Devils' deficit to 32-28 with 42 seconds remaining. Oregon coach Ernie Kent said the win was the result of weeks of hard practices. "It's good to see them respond, and it is even more important for them to see that we were right and just in terms of toughening them up and doing some things that make them more accountable."
